---
<Layout title="Sruthin Gaddam | Library Website Development">
    <div class="prose max-w-none">
        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-8">Library Website Development</h1>
        <div class="mb-12">
            <p>
                The WebUX team embarked on a journey to redesign and develop the Main Library website, an ambitious and a long-term project for our team. This endeavor offered a rare opportunity to collaborate closely with our designers to build the major components of our website. With the guidance from our team, I took the lead on developing key components—the Main Library Search, the Main Library Hours pages, the Main Library Homepage, Branch Library Homepages, Branch Library Search pages and the Main Library Spaces pages.
            </p>
            <h2>Library Search</h2>
            <p>
                The development of the Main Library Search began with building a flexible and robust backend system for search configurations. From the outset, the decision was made to make the search module configurable for non-developers, empowering Drupal admins with control over various aspects: adjusting the number of results per box, modifying the results box title, toggling display settings, and even customizing the order of results boxes (Figure 1).
            </p>
            <p>
                New functionality was introduced, allowing users to view results from a single source without being overwhelmed by the traditional bento box format. To meet the specific needs of librarians, EDS and FOLIO APIs were integrated, enabling users to retrieve call numbers and book availability in a more accessible way.
            </p>
            <p>
                I encountered a problem with the Springshare API’s inability to search databases—one that was overcome by developing a Drupal module capable of fetching database information from Springshare and indexing it into the backend search engine, SOLR. This functionality was further extended to Course Reserves, allowing course-related materials to be indexed in the search engine and enabling enhanced features such as keyword highlighting, searching by course number, instructor name, or course title. Boolean searches were also implemented, significantly improving the search capabilities. By December 2022, the search had been finalized (Figure 2) and transitioned to the Web Advisory Group for testing in early 2023. All the aforementioned improvements made our search more usable and robust compared to what we had on the old Library website (Figure3).  
            </p>
            <p>
                The same search module was also used to develop the Branch Library Search pages, which use the same backend that can be configured to add and remove search boxes on the Branch Library Search pages. 
            </p>
            <h2
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 bg-gray-800 bg-clip-padding rounded px-2">
            <Figure
