                />
        </div>
        <h2>Main Library and Branch Libraries Homepages</h2>
        <p>
            After the search was built, my focus shifted to an equally critical aspect—the development of the Main Library Homepage. This phase included designing and implementing essential sections such as Quick Links, Events & Workshops, News, Exhibits, and the Services section. Integrating external data sources required innovation, particularly when pulling event information from Springshare. To accomplish this, a new Drupal module was crafted, not only fetching events but also filtering them by category for a more refined user experience. The News, Exhibits and Services components were built directly within Drupal. After the redesign, our total homepage views are up from 241,154 to 312,912. This is comparing views on the old site (Figure 4) from Spring 2023 to views on the new site (Figure 5) in Fall 2023. 
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 bg-gray-800 bg-clip-padding rounded px-2">
            <Figure
                path="/src/assets/images/oldHomepage.png"
                alt="Main Library Homepage with search, events, and services sections"
                caption="Figure 4: MSU Library website homepage on the old site"
                width="100%"
                height="100%"
                />
            <Figure
                path="/src/assets/images/newHomepage.png"
                alt="Main Library Homepage with hours, events, and quick links sections"
                caption="Figure 5: MSU Library website homepage on the new site"
                width="100%"
                height="100%"
                />
        </div>
        <p>
            By January 2023, the Main Library Homepage was completed, and I moved on to the next set of milestones. February 2023 brought the development of specialized homepages for the Murray & Hong Special Collections, the Creative Solutions Center, and the Makerspace, Business Library, Art Library, Music Library, Map Library and other branch libraries—each designed to meet distinct needs while maintaining the cohesive vision of the redesigned library website. Below are the screenshots of the old Special Collections homepage (Figure 6) and the new Special Collections homepage (Figure 7).
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 bg-gray-800 bg-clip-padding rounded px-2">
            <Figure
                path="/src/assets/images/oldSpcHomepage.png"
                alt="Special Collections Library Homepage with search, and a text blurb about the library"
                caption="Figure 6: Special Collections homepage on the old website"
                width="100%"
                height="100%"
                />
            <Figure
                path="/src/assets/images/newSpcHomepage.png"
                alt="Special Collections Library Homepage with search, showcasing the collections on the homepage"
                caption="Figure 7: Special Collections homepage on the new website"
                width="100%"
                height="100%"
                />
        </div>
        <h2>Hours Pages</h2>
        <p>
            To modernize how library and branch hours were managed and displayed, our team transitioned to a new backend system. We selected Springshare as the platform for inputting hours and leveraged its API to dynamically retrieve and display hours for the main library and all branch locations.
            I developed a new hours page based on designs by our UX Designer, Shelby Kroske. The interface presents a clear week view of all library hours (Figure 8) and allows users to seamlessly switch to a month view for any selected library (Figure 9). Shelby and I collaborated closely to ensure the mobile experience was equally effective, carefully designing and implementing responsive layouts for both the week (Figure 10) and month (Figure 11) views to ensure clarity and usability on smaller screens.
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 bg-gray-800 bg-clip-padding rounded px-2">
            <Figure
